Use ASP.NET Core's **`WebApplicationFactory<T>`** (from `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing`) to create an in-memory test server, then pass its `HttpClient` into the MCP SDK's transport.

### Setup

```bash
dotnet add package Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing
dotnet add package ModelContextProtocol  # official C# MCP SDK
```

### Example test (xUnit)

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing;
using ModelContextProtocol.Client;
using ModelContextProtocol.Transport;

public class McpIntegrationTests
    : IClassFixture<WebApplicationFactory<Program>>
{
    private readonly WebApplicationFactory<Program> _factory;

    public McpIntegrationTests(WebApplicationFactory<Program> factory)
        => _factory = factory;

    [Fact]
    public async Task ListTools_ReturnsExpectedTools()
    {
        // WebApplicationFactory gives you an HttpClient wired to an
        // in-memory TestServer — no real port, no real network.
        var httpClient = _factory.CreateClient();

        // Use the SDK's Streamable-HTTP transport, injecting the test client
        var transport = new SseClientTransport(
            new SseClientTransportOptions
            {
                Endpoint = new Uri(httpClient.BaseAddress!, "/mcp"),
                // Name shown in protocol handshake
                Name = "integration-test"
            },
            httpClient   // ← the key: reuse the in-memory client
        );

        await using var mcpClient = await McpClientFactory.CreateAsync(transport);

        var tools = await mcpClient.ListToolsAsync();

        Assert.NotEmpty(tools);
        Assert.Contains(tools, t => t.Name == "my-tool");
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task CallTool_ReturnsCorrectResult()
    {
        var httpClient = _factory.CreateClient();

        var transport = new SseClientTransport(
            new SseClientTransportOptions
            {
                Endpoint = new Uri(httpClient.BaseAddress!, "/mcp"),
                Name = "integration-test"
            },
            httpClient
        );

        await using var mcpClient = await McpClientFactory.CreateAsync(transport);

        var result = await mcpClient.CallToolAsync(
            "my-tool",
            new Dictionary<string, object?> { ["input"] = "hello" });

        Assert.False(result.IsError);
        Assert.Contains("expected-output", result.Content[0].Text);
    }
}
```

### Why this works

| Piece | Role |
|---|---|
| `WebApplicationFactory<Program>` | Hosts your real `Program` startup in-process with a `TestServer` — no TCP port needed |
| `CreateClient()` | Returns an `HttpClient` whose `HttpMessageHandler` routes directly to the in-memory server |
| `SseClientTransport` / `StreamableHttpClientTransport` | Accepts an external `HttpClient`, so all MCP traffic flows through the test pipeline |

### Tips

- **Override services** for test doubles by calling `_factory.WithWebHostBuilder(b => b.ConfigureServices(...))`.
- **Ensure `Program` is accessible** — add `[assembly: InternalsVisibleTo("YourTestProject")]` or a partial class if `Program` is implicit (top-level statements).
- If your server uses the newer **Streamable HTTP** transport instead of SSE, swap `SseClientTransport` for `StreamableHttpClientTransport` with the same pattern.
